00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.000
I am a professor in the Biology
Department at MIT.

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:09.000
And I will be co-teaching this
course with Penny Chisholm who is a

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:14.000
professor in the Department of Civil
and Environmental Engineering,

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:19.000
as well as a professor in the
Biology Department.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:24.000
As well, Penny was recently
featured in the journal Nature.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:29.000
She is a very well-known
oceanographer who has become

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:34.000
deservedly famous for discovering a
very small bacterium that's capable

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:39.000
of carrying out photosynthesis.
For many years oceanographers used

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:43.000
filters whose holes were big enough
that this bacterium went through.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:47.000
And so when they were doing their
studies of the ocean and how the

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:51.000
biomass that was there and all the
fluxes and so on,

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:55.000
they didn't know this organism
existed which can form up to 50% of

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:00.000
the biomass in parts of the ocean.
So Penny is really a wonderful

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:05.000
lecturer, a wonderful person,
and she'll be teaching the component

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:10.000
of 7.014 which deals with ecology
and the environment.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:15.000
And this is a section of 7.
14 that makes it different from the

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:20.000
other two versions,
7.012 and 7.013. So for me

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:25.000
personally this is an absolutely
wonderful and exciting opportunity

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:30.000
to be able to teach this
Introductory Biology course.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:34.000
For some of you I know that biology
is going to either be a major part

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:38.000
of your career or quite possibly,
even if you're in engineering or

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:43.000
something else,
you will find yourselves working

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:47.000
with a biological system.
You can see that happening all over

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:52.000
campus these days that more and more
engineering departments are finding

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:56.000
that they're working on problems
that come from biology or have a

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:01.000
biological component.
I'm sure there are at least a few

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:05.000
of you here who are only here
because it's a required course and

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:10.000
you might well wish you
were somewhere else.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:14.000
However, I will do my best to try to
communicate to you why you need to

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:19.000
know some biology,
too. I think most of you know you

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:23.000
can hardly pick up a newspaper these
days without running into something

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:28.000
that demands a knowledge of biology,
something about stem cells,

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:33.000
something about cloning humans,
something about a new drug, lots of

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:37.000
things having to do with biological
affects on the environment

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:42.000
and so on.
You're also going to be confronted

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:46.000
with decisions about your health,
about the health of your loved ones

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:51.000
